Short Answers

  • 40% of the FRQ (2/5) are going to be short answer. Include Free=body diagrams (17% of points). Always write down how you got to your answer (Your scratch allat 43% of pts).
  • Questions focus on abstract concepts over numerical. Make sure you understand conceptual points
  • Past exams might not be that useful, because the formatted pattern changes in previous years. Graphing skills are very important.
    • We should cover this more
  • What would a bad answer have?
    • Not showing work
    • Not including an FBD
    • Just throwing straight answer.
    • Just have words
  • Just get any photo down

Experimental Design

  • Understand how to tackle it

    1. Understand what the question is asking
    2. Simple Complicated experiments will confuse you, KEEP IT SIMPLE STUPID
    3. Caution read carefully
    4. Photos make something to look at!
    5. Show your work
    6. Know all the equations on the equation page going in

  • What's an example of a bad one?

    • Super complicated with no cohesion, just straight yap
    • No pictures, nothing

Friction

Definition (Friction).

A force that opposes motion between two surfaces

2 main types

  • Static friction : Objects which are standing still
    • Usually larger than kinetic friction
  • Kinetic Friction: Objects which are moving
  • Friction is dependent on the nature of the surface and the normal force (Rough and adhesive makes more friction). Heavy also makes more
    Useful everywhere

8.1 Linear Momentum

Definition (Momentum).

Mass times velocity

Because it depends on mass and velocity, it is a vector
The unit is

Momentum is also equal to

Momentum is used in the real world for car crashes. Could be useful in basketball. How fast your running could change how you make a basket
When you're playing sports, you want to maximize the time you're applying any force. It'll make you faster

8.3 Conservation of Momentum

Basically if in any isolated system, not subjected to any net forces, the momentum is constant.
IF GRAVITY IS INVOLVED (on earth) MOMENTUM IS NOT CONSERVED

If we have a ball not moving at the top of a hill and it falls

8.4 Elastic Collisions

Any collision which conserves kinetic energy and momentum. Nothing runs away. Internal kinetic energy is the total kinetic energy before and after collision.

Elastic means useful energy is conserved

Inelastic means useful energy isn't conserved. It either left the system, or turned into heat
Total momentum before, equals total momentum after.

If you have an elastic collision and momentum, then momentum is conserved.

When would we use elastic vs inelastic collisions?

8.5 Inelastic

Energy isn't conserved.
Perfectly inelastic collision, means two objects stick together. This completely minimizes the final kinetic energy.

Was energy conserved here?
In an inelastic collision it isn't! In this case, where did the energy go? Thermal energy!
